00:31:27.975 --> 00:31:30.730
Could you describe
some of the side

00:31:30.730 --> 00:31:32.370
elements of creating the show?

00:31:32.370 --> 00:31:34.710
For example, the music,
the costuming-- there's

00:31:34.710 --> 00:31:39.460
a mix between Icelandic post
rock with Jonsi and Alex,

00:31:39.460 --> 00:31:41.440
and then just the period songs.

00:31:41.440 --> 00:31:45.537
How do create that
balance and mixture?

00:31:45.537 --> 00:31:47.120
SAM SHAW: Well, this
is a conversation

00:31:47.120 --> 00:31:50.640
that it started as a
conversation between me

00:31:50.640 --> 00:31:53.100
and Tommy Schlamme, our
director, about what

00:31:53.100 --> 00:31:54.700
the show should feel like.

00:31:54.700 --> 00:31:55.890
What should it look like?

00:31:55.890 --> 00:31:57.180
What should it feel like?

00:31:57.180 --> 00:31:59.580
This was the moment-- look,
I'd been a huge fan of His

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:01.110
I was a huge fan
of "The West Wing,"

00:32:01.110 --> 00:32:03.443
but it was a moment when I
understood that we were going

00:32:03.443 --> 00:32:05.200
to have a really great
partnership working

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:08.600
on "Manhattan" together,
because we both really responded

00:32:08.600 --> 00:32:13.300
to just this-- there's
something a little unsettling,

00:32:13.300 --> 00:32:15.900
and fundamentally strange,
and "Twilight Zone"

00:32:15.900 --> 00:32:17.880
like about the
subject matter itself.

00:32:17.880 --> 00:32:21.940
The Hill was this
odd, secret suburb,

00:32:21.940 --> 00:32:24.060
and it became really
important for us

00:32:24.060 --> 00:32:29.250
to find a way to tell a story
about this moment in the Second

00:32:29.250 --> 00:32:33.914
World War, but not to fall into
all the conventional tropes

00:32:33.914 --> 00:32:35.580
of World War II
storytelling, because we

00:32:35.580 --> 00:32:36.450
know what those feel like.

00:32:36.450 --> 00:32:38.750
There are incredible movies, and
there has been incredible TV.

00:32:38.750 --> 00:32:41.220
"Band of Brothers" is incredible
as a World War II story,

00:32:41.220 --> 00:32:42.678
but that's not what
this story was.

00:32:42.678 --> 00:32:44.530
This is a true life
science fiction story.

00:32:44.530 --> 00:32:46.920
So we were so lucky when
Jonsi and Alex came on

00:32:46.920 --> 00:32:50.680
to compose the score for
us in the first season,

00:32:50.680 --> 00:32:55.010
and that's like a metonymy
for the whole thing for us,

00:32:55.010 --> 00:32:56.770
which is that these
guys who in some ways

00:32:56.770 --> 00:32:59.790
were a crazy choice--
Jonsi is the front man

00:32:59.790 --> 00:33:02.810
of the Icelandic
rock band Sigur Ros,

00:33:02.810 --> 00:33:06.900
and their music is this
ambient, eerie, sometimes

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:08.310
electronic music.

00:33:08.310 --> 00:33:11.200
And there was just something
really fruitful and exciting

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:15.070
to us about the mix between
that sound and then these great

00:33:15.070 --> 00:33:17.030
period-- [INAUDIBLE]
you hear the radio,

00:33:17.030 --> 00:33:20.080
and it's-- hear Carmen
Miranda on the radio,

00:33:20.080 --> 00:33:22.090
and what's not to like?

00:33:22.090 --> 00:33:25.280
MARCY ROSS: Also it's the
timelessness of the piece

00:33:25.280 --> 00:33:26.300
and the subject matter.

00:33:26.300 --> 00:33:28.315
It's not just rooted
in that one event.

00:33:28.315 --> 00:33:29.940
SAM SHAW: Well that's
absolutely right.

00:33:29.940 --> 00:33:31.610
This is a very
important thing to us--

00:33:31.610 --> 00:33:36.070
is that we see this as an
incredibly contemporary story.

00:33:36.070 --> 00:33:37.330
It starts in 1943.

00:33:37.330 --> 00:33:40.420
We're up to 1945 by the
end of the second season,

00:33:40.420 --> 00:33:44.275
but I think it has a
real mirror to hold up

00:33:44.275 --> 00:33:45.650
to this contemporary
moment we're

00:33:45.650 --> 00:33:48.390
living in right now, and so
just the aesthetic of the show--

00:33:48.390 --> 00:33:51.640
how we shoot it, what the
visual reference points were,

00:33:51.640 --> 00:33:55.110
what it sounds like-- it was
really important that we lift

00:33:55.110 --> 00:33:59.100
it out of a box of feeling like
it's some sort of powdered wig

00:33:59.100 --> 00:34:04.059
period drama, but it is a little
harder to pin down than that.

00:34:04.059 --> 00:34:05.600
AUDIENCE: I guess
one other question.

00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:10.041
So as you're entering the season
two, the reception for the show

00:34:10.041 --> 00:34:10.790
has gotten bigger.

00:34:10.790 --> 00:34:13.260
I see that there's
reviews and recaps

00:34:13.260 --> 00:34:14.920
in "Scientific American."

00:34:14.920 --> 00:34:18.239
What's been the reception
among history buffs,

00:34:18.239 --> 00:34:21.250
historical enthusiasts,
or people whose relatives

00:34:21.250 --> 00:34:22.719
worked on the Hill?

00:34:22.719 --> 00:34:26.639
Are they clamoring for
lectures? [? How's it going? ?]

00:34:26.639 --> 00:34:28.555
SAM SHAW: It's been
really, really gratifying.

00:34:28.555 --> 00:34:32.790
I will say when we first started
the show out of the gates,

00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:35.380
I think we were the
only TV show-- there's

00:34:35.380 --> 00:34:38.949
a culture now online of doing
weekly reviews of episodes

00:34:38.949 --> 00:34:40.089
of TV.

00:34:40.089 --> 00:34:42.130
I'm not sure there's
another show on the air that

00:34:42.130 --> 00:34:44.860
was getting weekly recaps
written by "Scientific

00:34:44.860 --> 00:34:46.027
American," as you say, and--

00:34:46.027 --> 00:34:47.359
MARCY ROSS: "Popular Mechanics."

00:34:47.359 --> 00:34:49.409
SAM SHAW: "Popular
Mechanics," but that

00:34:49.409 --> 00:34:51.780
seemed like a really,
really pretty cool punk rock

00:34:51.780 --> 00:34:53.570
kind of thing to be a show
that was getting weekly reviews

00:34:53.570 --> 00:34:55.310
by "Popular Mechanics,"
but the truth

00:34:55.310 --> 00:34:57.140
is scientists in the
science community

00:34:57.140 --> 00:34:58.890
has been incredibly
supportive of the show

00:34:58.890 --> 00:34:59.940
and really welcoming.

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:03.390
I know there's a regular
Tuesday night pizza

00:35:03.390 --> 00:35:06.440
party at some bar in Los
Alamos where people watch

00:35:06.440 --> 00:35:07.740
the show and talk about it.

00:35:07.740 --> 00:35:07.840
MARCY ROSS: Have you gone?

00:35:07.840 --> 00:35:08.500
SAM SHAW: I have not gone.

00:35:08.500 --> 00:35:10.640
As I say, I can't watch
the show with other people.

00:35:10.640 --> 00:35:12.990
I'm too much of a hermit.

00:35:12.990 --> 00:35:14.560
Can't watch people
watch the show,

00:35:14.560 --> 00:35:17.327
but no, it's been
really gratifying.

